# 30-performance-rules.mdc

## General performance
- Avoid premature micro-optimizations, but do not ignore obvious inefficiencies.
- Prefer algorithms and data access patterns that scale with expected usage.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders, repeated queries, repeated parsing, and repeated network requests.
- Cache only where it provides clear value and does not risk stale or incorrect data.
- Actively choose more efficient approaches when they do not significantly increase complexity.

## Frontend performance
- Minimize large client bundles and unnecessary dependencies.
- Avoid shipping server-only logic to the client.
- Lazy load heavy or non-critical features when appropriate.
- Optimize images, fonts, and third-party scripts.
- Reduce total external requests and avoid unnecessary runtime work on initial load.
- Avoid unnecessary state updates and re-renders; ensure components only update when needed.

## Backend performance
- Avoid N+1 queries and repeated expensive calls inside loops.
- Select only needed fields from databases and APIs.
- Use pagination, limits, and streaming when datasets can grow.
- Be intentional about concurrency, timeouts, and backpressure.
- Avoid performing expensive operations repeatedly when results can be reused or cached safely.

## Measurement
- Prefer measured improvements over assumptions.
- Preserve or improve performance when modifying core paths.
- Respect project performance budgets and avoid adding heavy libraries without justification.

## Enforcement
- If a more efficient approach exists without significantly increasing complexity, prefer it.
- Do not over-optimize prematurely, but do not ignore obvious inefficiencies.
